text.label: Text
text.value: Albrecht Drer was born in Nuremberg on May 21, 1471. His father is a well-known goldsmith in the city, but originally comes from Hungary. With a population of more than 30,000, Nuremberg is Germany's second largest city and an international trade hub. Albrecht grows up in the lively craftsmen's quarter at the foot of the Burgberg. He has 17 brothers and sisters, most of whom, however, die very young.

text.label: Text
text.value: Woodcut with Nuremberg city view from Schedel's World Chronicle, sheet 99v/100r

text.label: Text
text.value: To become a painter, Drer had to spend many years as an apprentice. From 1486 to 1489/90 he was an apprentice to Nuremberg's best-known painter Michael Wolgemut. The following journeys as a journeyman took him to Basel, Strasbourg and the workshop of the late Martin Schongauer in Colmar, where he perfected his graphic techniques.

caption.label: Caption
caption.value: The video illustrates the production of a copperplate engraving, the most sophisticated graphic technique in Drer's time, which Drer introduced after his wandering years in Nuremberg. In the course of his career, he created more than 100 copperplate engravings.

text.label: Text
text.value: When Drer returned home from his wanderings in the spring of 1494, his father had already chosen a wife for him - Agnes, the daughter of a fellow craftsman. In Drer's day, arranged marriages were nothing unusual. Agnes manages Drer's household, takes care of his apprentices and his elderly mother, and helps sell his works. Although the marriage remains childless, Drer seems to have loved his wife very much.

text.label: Text
text.value: The 23-year-old Drer probably made this intimate drawing of "his Agnes" shortly before their wedding in the spring of 1494. Agnes was only 18 or 19 years old at the time. With quick pen strokes, Drer captures this moment of sleepy thoughtfulness. Agnes becomes one of Drer's favorite models.

text.label: Text
text.value: Probably in late 1495 or 1496, Drer travels south, from North to South Tyrol and on to Italy. Although exact dates are missing, Drer probably spends some time in Innsbruck as well as in the Trentino region before continuing his journey to Venice, then an important trading city with close ties to Nuremberg, including the printing trade.

text.label: Text
text.value: This small view of Innsbruck from the north side of the Inn River is full of life. Drawn in 1496, Drer not only depicts the cityscape along the Inn River and individual buildings, but also masterfully renders fleeting effects such as lighting effects or the reflection of houses in the water.

text.label: Text
text.value: After his return from Italy, Drer worked hard to build up a business and find new clients. He paints portraits and altarpieces for wealthy Nuremberg clients, but is best known for his novel woodcuts and highly refined copperplate engravings. Around 1500 he was already praised as the most famous artist in Germany.

text.label: Text
text.value: In 1500, Drer, now 29 years old, paints himself in an unusual Christ-like manner. The fur coat also refers to his social status as a respected artist and well-to-do citizen of Nuremberg.

text.label: Text
text.value: For Drer, nature is the "master of art". He is one of the first artists in Germany to study nature directly on site.

text.label: Text
text.value: The "Young Hare" from 1502 is one of Drer's most famous works. The detailed drawing of the animal still fascinates today.

text.label: Text
text.value: The "Feast of the Rosary" (1506) is Drer's most Italianate painting. Amidst the faithful gathered around the Madonna having a "Holy Conversation," Drer has depicted himself in the background, proudly presenting a sheet of paper with his signature. The majestic Madonna, the floating robes and beautifully shaded colors, the playful putti - all this is reminiscent of Venetian Renaissance paintings.

text.label: Text
text.value: In 1505-07 Drer travels to Italy for the second time. In Venice, he struggles to gain official recognition from Venetian artists, whom he suspects of secretly copying his prints. Finally, they praise his painting of the "Feast of the Rosary." Drer's success on the Italian market underscores his international reputation.

text.label: Text
text.value: Much of Drer's fame is due to his virtuoso graphic style. His contemporary Erasmus of Rotterdam wrote that Drer was able to create entire worlds with black and white lines alone, including intangibles such as sounds, atmospheric effects, and even emotions.

text.label: Text
text.value: Drer's "Melancholia" (1514) is his most famous master engraving. The winged female figure of Melancholia, lost in thought, is surrounded by meticulously rendered objects that reference geometry, astrology, and mathematics. The scribbling putto adds a playful touch to this enigmatic scene.

text.label: Text
text.value: In 1520-21 Drer spent a year in the Netherlands. From the commercial metropolis of Antwerp, he makes several trips to other art centers in Flanders, Brabant and the Rhineland. The trip is a triumph: artists, rich merchants, nobles and even the newly crowned Emperor Charles V receive him with great dignity. In a "travel diary" Drer records his itinerary, events, encounters and the works of art created on the journey. Together with the drawings created during the journey, the "Diary of the Dutch Journey" forms the most comprehensive autobiographical document of a Renaissance artist.

text.label: Text
text.value: Shortly after his arrival in Antwerp in August 1520, Drer depicted this view of the city's harbor. The quickly drawn scene is full of detail and gives a vivid picture of the bustling atmosphere on the banks of the Scheldt.

text.label: Text
text.value: Between 1525 and 1528, Drer published his three theoretical treatises, the "Theory of Perspective" (1525), the "Treatise on Fortifications" (1527) and the "Book of Proportions" (1528), which was published posthumously by his wife Agnes. Drer had been working on the texts and illustrations since the beginning of the 16th century, trying to decipher the "secrets of perspective" and various methods of calculating human proportions. Drer's original German versions were translated into Latin and other languages.

text.label: Content
text.value: <iframe frameborder="0" scrolling="no" style="border:0px" src="https://books.google.de/books?id=SpX3BoSucz0C&hl=de&pg=PA5&output=embed" width=500 height=650></iframe>

text.label: Text
text.value: Drer had worked on the "Book of Proportions" for almost 25 years. It describes various methods of calculating human proportions - male and female in different constitutions and even children. One chapter is devoted to movements, another passage to distortions.

text.label: Text
text.value: Drer died on April 6, 1528, at the age of 56, at his home in Nuremberg after a short illness. He was buried in the family vault of his parents-in-law in Nuremberg's Johannis Cemetery. His wife Agnes continued to run the workshop until her own death in 1539. Unlike most artists of his time, Drer was never forgotten by posterity - on the contrary. Thanks to his outstanding art and self-promotion, his fame remains to this day.

text.label: Text
text.value: Drer's grave has been an iconic site since the 16th century. In the 17th century, the painter and founder of the Nuremberg Art Academy, Joachim von Sandrart, donated a bronze plaque to honor his hero, and other artists sought to be buried alongside Drer in the Frey family tomb.

question.value: Which one is the genuine Drer artwork?

text.label: Text
text.value: Did you guess correctly? It's not easy, as Drer's works were frequently copied with great attention to detail. In this case, it was copied by Hans Hoffmann, who even signed the painting with Drer's iconic monogram 'AD.' If you look closely, you'll notice the year 1528 above it (the year of Drer's death).
